Build passes. Here's the approach:

**Use [`System.IO.Abstractions`](https://www.nuget.org/packages/System.IO.Abstractions)** — the battle-tested NuGet package for this exact problem. I've already:

1. Added the package and updated `ReportGenerator` to inject `IFileSystem` via its constructor
2. Replaced `File.*` / `Directory.*` calls with `fileSystem.File.*` / `fileSystem.Directory.*`

**Register in DI** (`Program.cs` or `Startup.cs`):
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**In tests**, use `MockFileSystem` (from `System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers`):
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddDirectory("/tmp/reports");

var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs);
generator.GenerateReport("sales");

Assert.True(mockFs.File.Exists(
    mockFs.AllFiles.Single(f => f.Contains("sales"))));
```

This avoids writing to real disk in tests and lets you assert on exactly what was written. The same pattern works for `ReadAllText` — just call `fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path)` instead of the static.
